## PB3(4/5): reentrancy panic example (informational; not in EMIT_TARGETS).
##
## Per GPT-5.5 entry 29 (PB3 R2 reentrancy policy): calling
## `signal.set(...)` from inside a subscriber body (i.e.,
## during an active notification) is V1-unsupported and panics
## at runtime. The runtime's `notifying: bool` flag is set true
## for the duration of `set`'s walk; any reentrant `set` or
## `subscribe` checks the flag and panics.
##
## Why panic instead of silently allowing? Per the design pass:
## R4 (tolerate via index walk + len snapshot) would force the
## V1 spec to define cascade semantics (re-fire all subscribers
## or just the late additions? what about unsubscribe during
## fire? does the cascade share the parent's notification
## context?) — these belong in PB4 once the canary exposes the
## use cases. R2 (panic) is strict-first; relax later.
##
## Generalizes cleanly to a future `Future<T>` async primitive:
## resolve-once + notify-waiters without arbitrary recursive
## resolve semantics.
##
## Expected runtime output (NOT in test/run goldens since the
## test harness doesn't yet have an expected-panic mode):
##
##   thread <id> panic: Rig Signal.set: reentrant set is not
##   supported in V1
##
## To verify by hand:
##   $ bin/rig run examples/signal_reentrant_set_panics.rig
##   (should panic with the message above)

sub main()
  sig: *Signal(Int) = *Signal(value: 0)
  # The subscriber's body calls sig.set(...) — reentrant set
  # during notification. Triggers the V1 panic guard.
  bad: *Closure() = *Closure(fn |+sig| sig.set(99))
  sig.subscribe(+bad)
  sig.set(1)                        # PANIC: reentrant set
